= demonsarise
## Demons Arise
To this settled way of thinking come demons…

Drawing arabesques with wheelies exemplifies following one's nose. We more-or-less design from what we see. See a compass; imagine a wheelie. Post-and-lintel, to be sure, but post-and-lintel works just fine — thank you — in all that doors require for letting people get around.

But along come arches — a disruptive technology, allowing piecemeal rocks to span greater distances than contiguous lintels, which, perforce, break when spans are too long. For wheelies, what disrupts is the [inverse discrete Fourier transform](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_Fourier_transform#Inverse_transform). With it we ditch step-and-repeat; the transform generates the entire arabesque in just one throw.

The shiv that cuts is this: Wheelies are cognates of _frequency domain_ points, plots that inhabit a discrete, one dimensional parameter space. The ordinates embody oscillatory magnitudes and phasings; abscissas reflect frequency of oscillation.
= figfive
===
![spectralspace](images/spectralspace.svg)
*5. Plotting _kth_ wheelie in a one dimensional, discrete, circular and finite frequency domain.*
===

|      1.  |The frequency domain is discrete, finite and circular:
|      1a.  |Its origin corresponds to a rotation rate of zero. Discrete frequencies, _ω_, mark off the abscissa. These are commensurate with wheelies' rotational rates.
|      1b.  |The abscissa wraps around. Clockwise and counterclockwise rotational coordinates extend from the origin's left and right, meeting at a _folding_ or [Nyquist sampling rate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyquist_rate) (_n_). This sets the space's extent: _2·n_.
|      1c.  |As a consequence of folding, addition and subtraction become [modular](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic). Subtrahends larger than their minuends do not produce negative results, but induce an implied addition of multiple extents: as many necessary to bring results into the interval _0,…,2·n–1_. Similarly, addends exceeding the extent invoke an implied subtraction, again as many necessary to bring the results into the same interval.
|      2.  |An ordinate in this domain constitutes a _displaced point rotating around an origin_. Ordinates, being complex, denote both magnitudes and angular offsets from a reference direction. One need not squint very hard to see how a wheelie, also spinning from an initial orientation, expresses a complex point tracing a circular path, with frequency marking completions per period.
|      3.  |A minimum Nyquist sampling rate may be chosen to distinguish, within one period, _at least_ two distinct orientations of the most rapidly spinning wheelie.

Transforming this space by way of the inverse discrete Fourier transform produces an aggregate oscillatory signal of complex values. These trace the ultimate wheelie tip on the complex plane. The path is cognate to frequency domain samples plotted through this scheme:

= mapwheelies
### Mapping Wheelies to the Frequency Domain
|      1.  |It's essential not to plot _single_ wheelies in the frequency domain but _sums_ along their chain.
|      1a.  |A wheelie reflects its own spin, and also that of its antecedents. Similarly for orientation.
|      2.  |Starting from the root wheelie, initialize aggregate sums for orientation, _Σθ_, and rotational rate, _Σω_, with the orientation of the root, _θ₀ → Σθ_, and the root's rotational rate, _±ω₀ → Σω_.
|      2a.  |If _Σω_ < 0, add twice the Nyquist rate: _Σω + 2·n → Σω_ in accordance with modular arithmetic.
|      3.  |With the current wheelie, decompose its radius, _r_, into complex components: _r_ → _r·cos(Σθ) + i·r·sin(Σθ)_.
|      4.  |Add this decomposed complex radius to the value at frequency domain coordinate _Σω_.
|      5.  |If there are no further wheelies in the chain, branch to 7. Otherwise:
|      6.  |Proceed to the next wheelie in the chain from the root. Add its orientation, _θ_, and rotational rate, _ω_, to aggregate sums:  _θ + Σθ → Σθ_, and _ω + Σω → Σω_.
|      6a.  |If _Σω_ < 0, then add the Nyquist rate: _Σω + 2·n → Σω_ in accordance to modular arithmetic. Branch to 3.
|      7.  |We've finished plotting. The inverse discrete Fourier transform generates the arabesque; we exit.
