## To There And Back Again
Suppose we already have an arabesque, or, more broadly, an arbitrary shape topologically equivalent to a circle, but which has been suitably worked over by an Old School ash, 18 inch Louisville Slugger® so as to appear, say, like a 1911 Goudy Bookletter ampersand, over which some tutorial writers seem obsessed. Are there wheelies that could generate it?
= figten
===
| ![goudyampersand](images/ampersand_circ.svg)
|*10. Circle ~~slightly~~ ~~somewhat~~ substantially dented into the shape of a 1911 Goudy Bookletter ampersand*
===
Let us take a broad view and regard an "arabesque" as any path which is topologically equivalent to a circle. We've noted that arabesques are cognates of frequency domain images.

To see how this is so, consider the coordinates of a complex plane point traveling along such a path. These coordinates vary over time and, as the point completes circuits the time-varying coordinates repeat — a "periodic signal". Taking the discrete Fourier transform of this periodic signal we generate the path's corresponding frequency domain image.

So far, so good: from the arabesque we have arrived at its frequency domain image. From there we might consider running [Mapping Wheelies to the Frequency Domain](#mapwheelies) backwards somehow, separating wheelie sums out into the wheelies themselves.

That, for the moment, may engender a certain angst. Are there specific chains of wheelies, also cognate to the frequency domain image — and, by extension, to the particular arabesques — that we'd have to find?

A counter example comes to the rescue. Consider the wheelie chain _Xn_:
|- wheelie | radius (_r_)| orientation (_θ_)| spin (_±ω_)|_Σθ_|_Σω_|_r·cos(Σθ)_|_i·r·sin(Σθ)_
| *   1* | *   2* | *  3* | *  4* | *  5* | *  6* | *     7* | *     8*
|X₀|0.5|30°|+1|30°|+1|0.43301|0.25000
|X₁|0.5|15°|+2|45°|+3|0.35355|0.35355
|X₂|0.125|30°|2n-7|75°|2n-4|0.03235|0.12074
|X₃|0.25|15°|+3|90°|2n-1|0.00000|0.2500

Compare columns (5) and (6) with the corresponding columns of chain [ _Wn_ ](#tabwn). Though the chains differ, the sums of _Σθ_ and _Σω_ both generate the same frequency domain image and, under the inverse discrete Fourier transform, would produce the same arabesque. Yes, the terms are in a different order, but the order of terms does not matter so long as we obtain particular frequency domain image. This counter example illustrates that there can be any number of wheelie chain progenitors to a given frequency domain image, from which a particular arabesque follows.

This eases our burden. Our search for wheelie chains to generate 1911 Goudy Bookletter ampersands becomes one of finding _any_ wheelie chain that sums to the desired frequency domain image. For example, for some permutation, _a_, of _n_ non-zero ordinates present in the frequency domain image, we may find a suitable set of wheelies just from an ordered sequence of differences:

===

$$
\begin{matrix}
W_{0} & = & a_0 \\
W_{1} & = & a_1 - a_0 \\
W_{2} & = & a_2 - a_1 \\
& \vdots & \\
W_{k} & = & a_k - a_{k-1} \\
& \vdots & \\
W_{n} & = & a_n - a_{n-1} \\
\end{matrix}
$$

===

so that ak arises from the wheelie sum: Wk + Wk-1 + … + W₁ + W₀.

While, in principle, we could use any permutation of non-zero ordinates, there is a practical aspect of differencing first the low rotational ordinates of the frequency domain: in the vast majority of cases, the oscillations with the largest swings tend to low frequencies, clustering around the origin _ω₀_ — not unlike discrete Fourier transforms of images. A generally small circle around the origin encompasses most of the information in an image. Tried-and-true Fourier compression schemes rely on retaining that small circle of coefficients and throwing out the rest — typically the majority — of coefficients. This suggests that we can approximate an ampersand fairly closely with a smallish number of aptly chosen, "highly energetic" wheelies that arise from the differences of the low-frequency coefficients.    


= reversemap
### Reverse Mapping Frequency Domain Coefficients


can of the arabesque and is commensurate to it and To put a stake in the ground, let us say that there are. In setting ourselves along this course, our feet land on a well-trodden path. Going back a decade or more, there have been eruptions of [fantastic constructions](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-qgreAUpPwM) of gyrating arrows that do etch-a-sketch things: drawing birds, flowers, even portraits of Jean-Baptiste Joseph Fourier or Santiago Ginnobili's [Homer Simpson](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QVuU2YCwHjw).

In this ovure, our wheelie is a pseudonym for an _epicycle_ and the rôle it plays is that of a brick: a building block with standard behaviors. Here, the behaviors are radius, _r_, orientation, _θ_ and spin, clockwise or otherwise, _±ω_. These come with attachment points for chaining them and out of them we may draw anything that pleases and is periodic — so long as we have the code.

The code, to wit: the particular settings _r, θ,_ and _±ω_ that, applied to wheelies in an orderly way, draws flowers, birds, Homer Simpsons or 1911 Goudy Bookletter ampersands. Hitherto we've been choosing settings by whimsy and seeing what twirls. Now we're walking backwards to _find_ settings _r, θ,_ and _±ω_ to draw preconceived whimsies: ampersands and such.

But, verily, walking backwards is what we _have_ been doing. Plotting wheelie sums in the frequency domain and harnessing the inverse discrete Fourier transform to plot spatial arabesques has a forward counterpart. Harness the (forward) discrete Fourier transform to produce the frequency domain image of the preconceived arabesque, and take differences of frequency domain values to find the wheelies. 


It turns out that we don't have to worry about that. There is something interesting about the four wheelies entabulated here:

